==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} as if *{{term||emplier}} < {{etyl|la}} {{term|implicare||to infold, involve}} < {{term|in||in}} + {{term|plicare||to fold}}

===Pronunciation===
*{{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ɪmˈplʌɪ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-imply.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*: {{rhymes|aɪ}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|impl|i|ed}}

# {{obsolete}} To [[enfold]], [[entangle]].
#*'''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', I.iv:
#*:And in his bosome secretly there lay / An hatefull Snake, the which his taile vptyes / In many folds, and mortall sting '''implyes'''.
# {{transitive}} To have as a [[necessary]] [[consequence]].
# {{transitive}} To express in a [[suggestive]] manner rather than as a direct [[statement]].
#: ''"Are you '''implying''' that I don't [[wash]] my hands?!"''
# {{transitive}} To [[suggest]] a [[logical]] [[inference]].

====Usage notes====
* This is a [[catenative]] verb that takes the ''gerund (-ing)''. See [[Appendix:English catenative verbs]]

